{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01L1PJWbRWqo4hkWCH9DV9Tr","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story file created at `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/4-3-trace-id-generation-injection.md`.\n\n**Summary:**\n- Story 4-3 (Trace ID Generation & Injection) created with 9 acceptance criteria, all tagged `<!-- verification: test-provable -->` — every AC is verifiable via build + test, no running app or Docker stack needed.\n- 4 implementation tasks: trace ID generator module, prompt injection formatter, WorkflowState extension, unit tests.\n- The story leverages the `appendSystemPrompt` forward-compat hook already in `agent-dispatch.ts` (story 4-1, line 14-15) and follows the immutable state pattern from `session-manager.ts` (story 4-2).\n- Key design: `trace-id.ts` is a standalone module — `agent-dispatch.ts` stays stateless, the workflow-engine (story 5-1) orchestrates the flow.\n\n## Session Issues\n\n- **No ambiguities found** — the epic definition in `epics-v2.md` (lines 397-409) was clear, and the architecture doc confirmed the trace ID format and injection mechanism.\n- **Risk: `trace_ids` field on WorkflowState** — adding an optional field to `WorkflowState` requires updating `isValidWorkflowState()`. If the validator rejects states with the new field before the code is deployed, existing states would break. The story handles this by making the field optional (`trace_ids?: string[]`) and validating it only when present.\n- **Observation:** All 9 ACs are `test-provable`. The trace ID module is pure logic with no I/O, and the persistence round-trip can be tested with temp directories. No AC requires runtime or environment verification.\n\n## Token Report\n\n- Total tool calls: 14\n- By tool: Bash: 1, Read: 5, Edit: 0, Grep: 4, Write: 1, Glob: 3\n- Largest Bash outputs (top 3 by line count): `ls implementation-artifacts/` (~170 lines)\n- Files read: 5 unique, 5 total reads (no file read 3+ times)\n- Redundant operations: none — each call gathered distinct context"},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: ade81eb778932dedd (use SendMessage with to: 'ade81eb778932dedd' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 54247\ntool_uses: 24\nduration_ms: 143794</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a1f3179e-0b63-4a22-aa4b-b755c26a5a4c","uuid":"51f63c28-f2f9-4950-ab99-cb9817f6422a","timestamp":"2026-04-02T20:28:21.849Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Run /create-story for story 4-3-trace-id-generation-injection. The sprint-status.yaml is at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/sprint-status.yaml. Auto-discover the next backlog story and create it. For each AC, append a verification tier tag using this decision tree:\n\n**Tier Decision Tree (append one `<!-- verification: {tier} -->` tag per AC):**\n- `test-provable` — AC can be verified by building the project and running tests/linters/grep. No running app needed. Examples: 'function X exists', 'type Y is exported', 'test Z passes', 'file has <300 lines'.\n- `runtime-provable` — AC requires running the app locally and checking its behavior (CLI output, HTTP response, process lifecycle). No Docker stack needed. Examples: 'CLI prints usage when invoked with --help', 'server responds 200 on /health', 'process exits 0 on valid input'.\n- `environment-provable` — AC requires a full environment (Docker stack, database, observability, multi-service interaction). Examples: 'logs appear in VictoriaLogs', 'metrics are emitted to VictoriaMetrics', 'container communicates with service X'.\n- `escalate` — AC genuinely cannot be automated (requires physical hardware, paid external service, human visual judgment). This is rare. Examples: 'UI looks correct on mobile', 'payment processes successfully in production'.\n\nDefault to `test-provable` when unsure. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sp